Note:
CHANNEL - Typed thread-safe FIFO message-passing channel.

A Channel<T> is a thread-safe FIFO queue used for inter-thread communication.

Channel modes:
- capacity == 0 -> unbounded (sender never blocks on capacity; only memory limits)
- capacity > 0  -> bounded; sender blocks when buffer is full

Channel structure layout (64 bytes):
  offset 0:  mutex_ptr        (8 bytes) - underlying mutex
  offset 8:  not_empty_cv     (8 bytes) - condvar receivers wait on
  offset 16: not_full_cv      (8 bytes) - condvar senders wait on (bounded)
  offset 24: head_node        (8 bytes) - pointer to head of singly-linked list
  offset 32: tail_node        (8 bytes) - pointer to tail of list
  offset 40: count            (8 bytes) - number of buffered messages
  offset 48: capacity         (8 bytes) - 0 = unbounded, otherwise bound
  offset 56: closed_flag      (8 bytes) - 0 = open, 1 = closed

Node layout (16 bytes):
  offset 0: value_ptr (8 bytes) - generic value (caller manages T's memory)
  offset 8: next_ptr  (8 bytes) - next node, 0 if tail

Dependencies:
- threading/sync_core.runa (mutex, condvar)
- memory/layout.runa (allocate/deallocate)
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/sync_core.runa" as Sync
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Mem

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Channel layout constants
Note: ============================================================================

Constant CHAN_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV as Integer is 8
Constant CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV as Integer is 16
Constant CHAN_OFF_HEAD as Integer is 24
Constant CHAN_OFF_TAIL as Integer is 32
Constant CHAN_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 40
Constant CHAN_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 48
Constant CHAN_OFF_CLOSED as Integer is 56
Constant CHAN_STRUCT_SIZE as Integer is 64

Constant CHAN_NODE_VALUE as Integer is 0
Constant CHAN_NODE_NEXT as Integer is 8
Constant CHAN_NODE_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: Return codes
Constant CHAN_OK as Integer is 1
Constant CHAN_ERR_CLOSED as Integer is 0
Constant CHAN_ERR_FULL as Integer is -1
Constant CHAN_ERR_EMPTY as Integer is -2
Constant CHAN_ERR_INVALID as Integer is -3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Channel Lifecycle
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
A channel is created with optional bounded capacity. Capacity 0 means unbounded
(senders never block on capacity, but memory is still finite). Capacity > 0
provides backpressure via condvar-based blocking.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
We allocate the 64-byte channel record on the owned heap, then allocate the
underlying mutex and two condvars. If any sub-allocation fails we roll back
prior allocations to avoid leaks.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Channel creation is O(1) plus three syscall-backed primitive allocations.
Reuse channels rather than recreating them in hot loops.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Channels store raw pointers as message values. Callers are responsible for
ensuring values remain valid for the channel lifetime, or for copying values
into channel-owned storage prior to send.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_create" takes capacity as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate channel record
    Let ch be proc allocate from Memory with CHAN_STRUCT_SIZE
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create underlying mutex
    Let mutex_ptr be proc mutex_create from Sync
    If mutex_ptr is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with ch
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create not_empty condvar
    Let not_empty_cv be proc condvar_create from Sync
    If not_empty_cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mutex_ptr
        proc deallocate from Memory with ch
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create not_full condvar
    Let not_full_cv be proc condvar_create from Sync
    If not_full_cv is equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from Sync with not_empty_cv
        proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mutex_ptr
        proc deallocate from Memory with ch
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Clamp negative capacity to 0 (unbounded)
    Let cap be capacity
    If cap is less than 0:
        Set cap to 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize all fields
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX, mutex_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV, not_empty_cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV, not_full_cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_HEAD, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_TAIL, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CAPACITY, cap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED, 0

    Return ch
End Process

@Reasoning
Destroying a channel frees the linked list of buffered nodes, then the
synchronization primitives, then the channel record itself. Any messages
still buffered are dropped (caller's responsibility to drain first if values
have non-trivial ownership).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Walk the head pointer freeing nodes, then destroy each synchronization
primitive, then free the channel record.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(n) in the number of buffered nodes. Drain channels before destroying when
ownership of message payloads matters.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The channel must not be in use by other threads when destroyed. Use
channel_close + drain instead for graceful shutdown.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_destroy" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Note: Free any remaining node chain
    Let node be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_HEAD
    While node is not equal to 0:
        Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with node, CHAN_NODE_NEXT
        proc deallocate from Memory with node
        Set node to next
    End While

    Note: Destroy sync primitives
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    Let not_empty_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV
    Let not_full_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV
    proc condvar_destroy from Sync with not_full_cv
    proc condvar_destroy from Sync with not_empty_cv
    proc mutex_destroy from Sync with mutex_ptr

    proc deallocate from Memory with ch
    Return CHAN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Send operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Internal helper: enqueue a value onto a channel that the caller has already
locked. Returns 1 on success, 0 on allocation failure. Caller must hold the
mutex when calling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Allocate a node, write the value pointer and a zero next pointer, then link
it onto the tail of the channel's queue. Increment the count.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) enqueue using head/tail pointers.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller MUST hold the channel mutex.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_enqueue_locked" takes ch as Integer, value_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    Let node be proc allocate from Memory with CHAN_NODE_SIZE
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with node, CHAN_NODE_VALUE, value_ptr
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with node, CHAN_NODE_NEXT, 0

    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_TAIL
    If tail is equal to 0:
        Note: Queue empty - this node becomes both head and tail
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_HEAD, node
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_TAIL, node
    Otherwise:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with tail, CHAN_NODE_NEXT, node
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_TAIL, node
    End If

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
    Let new_count be count plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT, new_count
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Blocking send. If the channel is bounded and full, the sender waits on
not_full_cv until either space is available or the channel is closed.
Sending on a closed channel returns CHAN_ERR_CLOSED.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Acquire the mutex, check closed flag, then check capacity bound in a
loop (re-check after wake to defend against spurious wakeups). When space
is available, enqueue, signal not_empty_cv, release mutex, return OK.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path (uncontended unbounded send) is one mutex acquire + one allocation
+ one condvar signal + one mutex release.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
The value pointer is stored by reference; caller retains responsibility for
the lifetime of the underlying object.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_send" takes ch as Integer, value_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Note: Closed channels reject sends
    Let closed be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED
    If closed is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
    End If

    Note: For bounded channels, wait while full
    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CAPACITY
    If capacity is greater than 0:
        Let not_full_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV
        Let waiting be 1
        While waiting is equal to 1:
            Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
            Let now_closed be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED
            If now_closed is not equal to 0:
                proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
                Return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
            End If
            If count is less than capacity:
                Set waiting to 0
            Otherwise:
                proc condvar_wait from Sync with not_full_cv, mutex_ptr
            End If
        End While
    End If

    Note: Enqueue the value
    Let ok be proc channel_enqueue_locked with ch, value_ptr
    If ok is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Note: Signal a waiting receiver
    Let not_empty_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV
    proc condvar_signal from Sync with not_empty_cv

    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return CHAN_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Non-blocking send. Returns immediately with CHAN_ERR_FULL if the channel is
bounded and full, or CHAN_ERR_CLOSED if closed.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Acquire mutex, perform closed and capacity checks without waiting, enqueue
if possible, signal not_empty_cv, release mutex.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Always returns within bounded time - no condvar wait.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Same as channel_send.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_try_send" takes ch as Integer, value_ptr as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let closed be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED
    If closed is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
    End If

    Let capacity be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CAPACITY
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
    If capacity is greater than 0:
        If count is greater than or equal to capacity:
            proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
            Return CHAN_ERR_FULL
        End If
    End If

    Let ok be proc channel_enqueue_locked with ch, value_ptr
    If ok is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let not_empty_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV
    proc condvar_signal from Sync with not_empty_cv

    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return CHAN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Receive operations
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Internal helper: dequeue a value from a channel that the caller has already
locked. Returns the value pointer, or 0 if the queue is empty. Caller must
hold the mutex when calling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Pop the head node, unlink it, decrement count, free the node, return the
stored value pointer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) dequeue.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller MUST hold the channel mutex.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_dequeue_locked" takes ch as Integer, out_value_ptr_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_HEAD
    If head is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_value_ptr_holder, 0, 0
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with head, CHAN_NODE_VALUE
    Let next be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with head, CHAN_NODE_NEXT
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_HEAD, next
    If next is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_TAIL, 0
    End If

    proc deallocate from Memory with head

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
    Let new_count be count minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT, new_count

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_value_ptr_holder, 0, value_ptr
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Blocking receive. Returns CHAN_OK with the received pointer written to
out_value_ptr_holder. Returns CHAN_ERR_CLOSED only when the channel is
closed AND the buffer is empty (draining semantics).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Acquire the mutex, loop until either a value can be dequeued or the channel
is empty-and-closed, signal not_full_cv after dequeue so any blocked
senders can proceed, release mutex.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Hot path (non-empty receive) is one mutex acquire + one node free + one
condvar signal + one mutex release.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-supplied out_value_ptr_holder must point to writable 8-byte storage.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_receive" takes ch as Integer, out_value_ptr_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If out_value_ptr_holder is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let not_empty_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV
    Let waiting be 1
    While waiting is equal to 1:
        Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
        If count is greater than 0:
            Set waiting to 0
        Otherwise:
            Let closed be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED
            If closed is not equal to 0:
                proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_value_ptr_holder, 0, 0
                proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
                Return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
            End If
            proc condvar_wait from Sync with not_empty_cv, mutex_ptr
        End If
    End While

    Let ok be proc channel_dequeue_locked with ch, out_value_ptr_holder
    If ok is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return CHAN_ERR_EMPTY
    End If

    Note: Wake any sender blocked on capacity bound
    Let not_full_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV
    proc condvar_signal from Sync with not_full_cv

    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return CHAN_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Non-blocking receive. Returns CHAN_OK with value written if a message was
available, or CHAN_ERR_EMPTY immediately if empty (regardless of closed
state - the buffer might still drain).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Acquire mutex, dequeue if anything is buffered, otherwise return EMPTY.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Always returns within bounded time.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Same as channel_receive.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_try_receive" takes ch as Integer, out_value_ptr_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If out_value_ptr_holder is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
    If count is equal to 0:
        proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_value_ptr_holder, 0, 0
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Let closed be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED
        If closed is not equal to 0:
            Return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
        End If
        Return CHAN_ERR_EMPTY
    End If

    Let ok be proc channel_dequeue_locked with ch, out_value_ptr_holder
    If ok is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
        Return CHAN_ERR_EMPTY
    End If

    Let not_full_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV
    proc condvar_signal from Sync with not_full_cv

    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return CHAN_OK
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Closing & inspection
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Closing a channel marks it as closed and wakes ALL blocked senders and
receivers. Receivers continue to receive any buffered messages until the
buffer is drained; subsequent receives return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Set the closed flag under the lock, broadcast both condvars so any waiters
can re-check state and unblock.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant time plus condvar broadcast cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Closing is idempotent. Closing an invalid channel returns CHAN_ERR_INVALID.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_close" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr

    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED, 1

    Let not_empty_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_EMPTY_CV
    Let not_full_cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_NOT_FULL_CV
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with not_empty_cv
    proc condvar_broadcast from Sync with not_full_cv

    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return CHAN_OK
End Process

@Reasoning
Inspection helpers for diagnostics and adaptive scheduling. All require
acquiring the mutex to avoid torn reads.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Take the lock, read the field, release the lock, return the field.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
O(1) but pays mutex acquisition cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Safe to call from any thread.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "channel_length" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Let count be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_COUNT
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return count
End Process

Process called "channel_capacity" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CAPACITY
End Process

Process called "channel_is_closed" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    If ch is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mutex_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_lock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Let closed be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with ch, CHAN_OFF_CLOSED
    proc mutex_unlock from Sync with mutex_ptr
    Return closed
End Process

Process called "channel_is_empty" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    Let n be proc channel_length with ch
    If n is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Select
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
channel_select waits on a list of channels and returns the index of the
first channel that has a message available. The list is passed as an array
of channel pointers, count is the length. Returns -1 on invalid input. The
received value is written into out_value_ptr_holder and the index is
returned. Polling-based for simplicity and portability.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Loop: try non-blocking receive on each channel in order. If any succeeds,
return its index. If none succeeds, yield the thread and retry. A closed
channel that is empty is reported via setting *out_index = i and returning
CHAN_ERR_CLOSED so callers can act on shutdown.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
This is busy-poll select (cooperatively yielding). For high-throughput
multi-way wait, a single shared condvar selector is preferable and is
provided via channel_select_blocking_index below.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Caller-supplied array must be valid for count entries. out_index_holder and
out_value_ptr_holder must be writable 8-byte locations.
@End Security_Scope

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/threading.runa" as Threading

Process called "channel_select" takes channels_array as Integer, count as Integer, out_index_holder as Integer, out_value_ptr_holder as Integer returns Integer:
    If channels_array is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If count is less than or equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If out_index_holder is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If
    If out_value_ptr_holder is equal to 0:
        Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
    End If

    Let polling be 1
    While polling is equal to 1:
        Let all_closed be 1
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let offset be i multiplied by 8
            Let ch be proc memory_get_int64 from Mem with channels_array, offset
            If ch is not equal to 0:
                Let rc be proc channel_try_receive with ch, out_value_ptr_holder
                If rc is equal to CHAN_OK:
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_index_holder, 0, i
                    Return CHAN_OK
                End If
                If rc is not equal to CHAN_ERR_CLOSED:
                    Set all_closed to 0
                End If
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        If all_closed is equal to 1:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_index_holder, 0, 0
            proc memory_set_int64 from Mem with out_value_ptr_holder, 0, 0
            Return CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
        End If

        Note: Cooperative yield between poll rounds
        proc platform_thread_yield from Threading
    End While

    Return CHAN_ERR_INVALID
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Notes on usage
Note: ============================================================================

Note:
Producer-consumer pattern:
  Let ch be channel_create(16)        Note: bounded with 16 slot capacity
  Thread A: channel_send(ch, value_ptr)
  Thread B: channel_receive(ch, &result_ptr)
  Shutdown: channel_close(ch)
  Drain:    while channel_try_receive returns CHAN_OK: handle msg
            channel_destroy(ch)

Closed semantics:
- send on closed   -> CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
- recv on closed AND empty -> CHAN_ERR_CLOSED
- recv on closed but non-empty -> CHAN_OK (drains buffer)
:End Note
